Sorting Algorithms :

Introduction

Sorting is the process of arranging data in a specific order, such as ascending or descending.
Sorting improves the efficiency of searching, data processing, and other algorithms.

Common Sorting Algorithms

1. Bubble Sort
Repeatedly compares adjacent elements and swaps them if they are in the wrong order.
Simple but inefficient for large datasets.
Best Case: O(n) (already sorted)
Average Case: O(n²)
Worst Case: O(n²)

2. Insertion Sort
Builds the sorted array one element at a time by inserting each element into its correct position.
Efficient for small or nearly sorted datasets.
Best Case: O(n)
Average Case: O(n²)
Worst Case: O(n²)

3. Heap Sort
Uses a Binary Heap data structure to sort elements.
First builds a max heap, then repeatedly extracts the maximum element.
Provides consistent performance.
Best Case: O(n log n)
Average Case: O(n log n)
Worst Case: O(n log n)

4. Quick Sort
Uses the Divide and Conquer technique.
Selects a pivot and partitions the array around it.
Very fast in practice but performance depends on pivot selection.
Best Case: O(n log n)
Average Case: O(n log n)
Worst Case: O(n²) (poor pivot selection)

5. Merge Sort
Also uses the Divide and Conquer technique.
Recursively divides the array into halves and merges them in sorted order.
Stable and efficient for large datasets.
Best Case: O(n log n)
Average Case: O(n log n)
Worst Case: O(n log n)

Time Complexity Comparison

| Sorting Algorithm | Best Case  | Average Case | Worst Case |
| ----------------- | ---------- | ------------ | ---------- |
| Bubble Sort       | O(n)       | O(n²)        | O(n²)      |
| Insertion Sort    | O(n)       | O(n²)        | O(n²)      |
| Heap Sort         | O(n log n) | O(n log n)   | O(n log n) |
| Quick Sort        | O(n log n) | O(n log n)   | O(n²)      |
| Merge Sort        | O(n log n) | O(n log n)   | O(n log n) |


Key Points
Bubble Sort: Easy to implement but slow for large datasets.
Insertion Sort: Best for small or nearly sorted data.
Heap Sort: Consistent performance with no worst-case degradation.
Quick Sort: Fastest on average but can degrade to O(n²).
Merge Sort: Stable and efficient, but requires extra memory.
Quick Sort and Merge Sort are widely used for large datasets due to their average O(n log n) performance.